Rude, crude and above all dumb,  shows like "Fear Factor" are part of  the mainstreaming of  a gross new world of  television.
<P>


<font  face="times new roman"><b><a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2002/02/04/arts/_04KEYS.html?todaysheadlines">Loving and Losing to Chase the Blues</a></b><br>
The talented R &amp; B singer Alicia Keys  played a concert at Radio City Music Hall on Friday  that was a  night of celebration, not innovation.
<P>
</font>


<font  face="times new roman"><b><a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2002/02/04/sports/football/04MUSI.html?todaysheadlines">Singers Merge Politics With Patriotism</a></b><br>
Sunday's pregame and halftime shows were, as they were meant to be, jarringly different from most Super Bowls, but it was easy to see where it all came from.
<P>
</font>













